Univariate Exploration¶

Defining a Function for a Univariate Histogram¶

In [ ]:
# Defining a function for plotting univariate histograms
def univariate_histogram(data, x_col, title, y_label, bins=8):
    """
    Plots a univariate histogram.

    Parameters:
    data: The dataset to be plotted.
    x_col: The column to be plotted on the x-axis.
    title: The title of the plot.
    y_label: The label of the y-axis.
    bins: The number of bins to be used in the histogram.

    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(18, 6))
    
    # Plotting the histogram
    plt.hist(data=data, x=x_col, bins=bins)
    
    # Setting title, labels, and other plot aesthetics
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xlabel('Date', labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.xticks(pd.date_range(data[x_col].min(), data[x_col].max(), freq='W'))
    plt.ylabel(y_label, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Defining a Bar Chart Function¶

In [ ]:
def univariate_bar_chart(data, x_col, y_col, title, x_label, y_label):
    """
    Plots a univariate bar chart.

    Parameters:
    data: The dataset to be plotted.
    x_col: The column to be plotted on the x-axis.
    y_col: The column to be plotted on the y-axis.
    title: The title of the plot.
    x_label: The label of the x-axis.
    y_label: The label of the y-axis.
    """
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
    
    # Plotting the bar chart
    plt.bar(data=data, x=x_col, height=y_col)
    
    # Setting title, labels, and other plot aesthetics
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    
    # Calculating the number of weeks between the min and max date for bins
    num_weeks = int((data[x_col].max() - data[x_col].min()).days / 7) + 1
    plt.xticks(pd.date_range(data[x_col].min(), data[x_col].max(), freq='W'))
    
    plt.xlabel(x_label, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Bivariate Exploration¶

Defining a Function for Box Plots with Swarm Overlay¶

In [ ]:
def box_plot_swarm_overlay(data, x_col, y_col, title, x_label, y_label):
    """
    Plots a box plot and swarm plot overlay.

    Parameters:
    data: The dataset to be plotted.
    x_col: The column to be plotted on the x-axis.
    y_col: The column to be plotted on the y-axis.
    title: The title of the plot.
    x_label: The label of the x-axis.
    y_label: The label of the y-axis.
    """
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
    
    # Plotting the box plot and swarm plot overlay
    sns.boxplot(x=data[x_col], y=data[y_col], palette="Blues")
    sns.swarmplot(x=data[x_col], y=data[y_col], color="red", size=3)
    
    # Setting title, labels, and other plot aesthetics
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xlabel(x_label, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Defining a function to extract the month from a specified date column and add it as a new 'Month' column to the DataFrame
def extract_month(df, date_col):
    """
    Extract the month from a specified date column and add it as a new 'Month' column to the DataFrame.
    
    Parameters:
    df: DataFrame containing the date column.
    date_col: Column name containing the date values.
    """
    
    df['Month'] = pd.to_datetime(df[date_col]).dt.month
In [ ]:

In [ ]:
# Plotting a scatter plot of 'Transaction Date' vs 'Donation Amount' from the 'donations_2022' dataset

# Converting 'Transaction Date' to datetime format
donations_2023['Transaction Date'] = pd.to_datetime(donations_2023['Transaction Date'])

# Converting datetime to ordinal numbers for plotting
x_dates = donations_2023['Transaction Date']
x_ord = x_dates.apply(lambda x: x.toordinal())

# Plotting a scatter plot with a regression line
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
sns.regplot(x=x_ord, y=donations_2023['Donation Amount'])

# Setting the x-ticks to be the original dates
plt.xticks(x_ord.unique(), x_dates.dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d').unique(), rotation=90)

plt.title('Donation Amounts (in USD) from 2023-03-28 to 2023-06-26', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Transaction Date', labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Donation Amount (in USD)', labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

General Observations:

  • The scatter plot displays sporadic distribution of donation amounts across time, indicating unpredictable donations.
  • Days with high donations contrast with days of lower donations, hinting at sporadic donor engagement.
  • Most donations lie within a specific range, with few higher outliers, suggesting a common donation bracket.

Defining a Scatter Plot Function¶

In [ ]:
def scatter_plot(df, x_col, y_col, size_col, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    """
    Plot a scatter plot with the specified columns and aesthetics.

    Parameters:
    df: DataFrame containing the columns to be plotted.
    x_col: The column to be plotted on the x-axis.
    y_col: The column to be plotted on the y-axis.
    size_col: The column to be plotted as the size of the points.
    title: The title of the plot.
    xlabel: The label of the x-axis.
    ylabel: The label of the y-axis.
    """
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x=x_col, y=y_col, size=size_col, sizes=(30, 250), alpha=0.6)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', pad=15)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, labelpad=25, fontsize=12)
    
    plt.legend(title=size_col, loc='upper left', fontsize=12, title_fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

  • Some days with larger dots do not have a correspondingly high number of clicks. This might imply that certain days, despite the higher advertising spend, did not necessarily yield a higher engagement.

Relationships Observed:

  • There doesn't appear to be a clear positive correlation between the size of the dots (Cost) and the number of clicks. This implies that spending more doesn't necessarily guarantee more clicks on a given day.
  • The variability in the number of clicks, despite the associated costs, suggests that factors other than advertising spend might be influencing user engagement. This could be related to the content of the ads, the platforms they were shown on, or external events affecting user behavior.

Conclusions¶

Summary of Main Findings:¶

1. Campaign Engagement:¶

  • The Google Ads campaigns for both adoptions and donations showed variability in terms of engagement.
  • Clicks fluctuated over time, with some days seeing notably higher or lower engagement compared to others.
  • Notably, the adoption campaign had a wider distribution and higher density of clicks compared to the donation campaign, suggesting a stronger overall engagement for adoption-related ads.

2. Effect of Advertising Spend:¶

  • A direct correlation between the advertising spend (Cost) and the number of clicks was not consistently observed.
  • This suggests that higher spending did not always guarantee more clicks or engagement.
  • This pattern was evident across both the adoption and donation campaigns.

3. Adoptions by Breed:¶

  • The distribution of adoptions varied significantly by breed. Domestic Shorthairs, for instance, had the highest number of adoptions, followed by breeds like Domestic Medium Hair and Domestic Long Hair.
  • The relationship between advertising costs and clicks also varied by breed, indicating that the campaign's effectiveness was breed-dependent.

4. Interactions between Features:¶

  • The size encoding of the scatter plots (representing Cost) revealed that on some days, despite higher advertising spends, the campaigns did not necessarily yield more engagement.
  • The facet plots further emphasized the breed-specific variability in the relationship between advertising costs and engagement.

Reflection on the Data Exploration Process:¶

1. Univariate Exploration:¶

  • Initial exploration focused on understanding the distribution of individual variables. Histograms, box plots, and violin plots provided insights into the central tendencies and spread of data like clicks and donation amounts.

2. Bivariate Exploration:¶

  • As I moved to bivariate exploration, relationships between two variables were analyzed. Scatter plots, for instance, helped visualize the relationship between clicks and dates, highlighting the variability in engagement over time.

3. Multivariate Exploration:¶

  • The multivariate analysis brought in an added layer of complexity. By introducing a third variable, such as Cost, using size encoding in scatter plots, I observed deeper interactions.
  • The use of facet plots allowed for a segmented analysis based on categories like 'Primary Breed', providing breed-specific insights.

4. Data Wrangling and Cleaning:¶

  • During the exploration, the need for data cleaning and merging became evident. Efforts were made to merge relevant datasets based on common attributes, enabling a more comprehensive analysis.
  • Handling missing values, adjusting data types, and dealing with outliers were crucial steps to ensure the integrity and reliability of the findings.

5. Visualization Challenges and Adjustments:¶

  • Throughout the exploration, various visualization challenges arose, from overlapping labels to inconsistent axis scales. Iterative adjustments and refinements were made to ensure clarity and accuracy in data representation.

6. Conclusion:¶

  • The data exploration journey was both informative and enlightening. It emphasized the importance of a systematic approach, starting from univariate analysis and building up to multivariate interactions.
  • The findings underscored the value of data-driven decision-making. Understanding how advertising spend translates to engagement, and how this relationship varies by factors like breed, can inform future campaign strategies and resource allocation.
